[{'created': '2015-10-22 20:15:32.000000000', 'message': 'Mysql file handles not correctly configured

The mysql database and the OS were using different settings for
max file handles, which ultimately can result in DB crashes.
This fix makes sure that the OS and the DB are synchronized
for the maximum file handle limits.
Additionally galera_file_limits was increased to 65k

Change-Id: I06c1da3c5d7ad81540d5e8ddc1b1bc7b4868bc71
Closes-Bug: #1509078
'}]
commit_message:
Mysql file handles not correctly configured

The mysql database and the OS were using different settings for
max file handles, which ultimately can result in DB crashes.
This fix makes sure that the OS and the DB are synchronized
for the maximum file handle limits.
Additionally galera_file_limits was increased to 65k

Change-Id: I06c1da3c5d7ad81540d5e8ddc1b1bc7b4868bc71
Closes-Bug: #1509078

commit_message:
Make the container cache resolvers configurable

This change simply makes it possible for a deployer to change
the in container resolvers.

In the bootstrap-aio script the resolvers are being set in the
user_variables so containers are using the same resolvers as the
host.

Change-Id: Id7ab3632217c3eb2217a308d7226736a67900da5
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Return 403 instead of 401 HTTP Response

401 Unauthorized is the HTTP status code used for authentication
errors for eg. Missing or Bad Authentication. 403 Forbidden
response is used for denying permission to access resources
for a correctly authenticated user.
This fix corrects the mistake in the api.

Change-Id: I0903b226cfe32a7aed69d265a27ca21d7cc9b98e
Closes-Bug:1477013

What do you exactly mean, Sebastian? If you are talking about fuel-web, I'm under impression that we first of all need to run it locally with tox. Am I missing anything... ?"}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-10-16 07:15:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, you guys missed the fact that nailgun tests make use of a database quite heavily (on FuelCI they actually create 4 dbs for 4 paraller test runs). How such tests looks on openstack infra? When I was checking it last time (few weeks ago) they were just experimenting with jobs that has need DB (I'm not talking about devstack jobs, but jobs like "gate-some-project-python27".

Additionally: how will we tackle the fact that there is (AFAIK) no jobs that support ruby or nodejs (UI).
It looks like there is no plan, there was an action item on weekly meeting to send it to openstack-dev ML but it didn't happen. There are just some patches appearing here and there, but still no info. commit_message:
Use "secret=True" for password-related options

This makes sure the value of the option is not leaked in the logs.

Found using bandit.

Change-Id: I6db2eea1d3f1ad3cacb749dbb9766c5d32cf047f

(4 comments)

I disagree that there needs to be more pondering into getting this into the stack.  If we're going to do it I'd argue that it needs to be done within a major release, which can be done in this release, and can be part of the already accepted venv spec. 

As for the additional code path'ing we can almost guarantee that repo infrastructure will be available to the deployment. As such having the role check for an available download seems like a logical choice in terms of dictating whether or not the venv is built in-place or downloaded. Having the downloadable venvs gives us the ability ensure package versions for deployers within a given release, consistency throughout the stack for a given service, and will work for both containers and on metal."}, {'account_id': 7353, 'date': '2015-10-20 00:50:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

The change builds venvs in a single repo container and then
ships them to to all targets. The built venvs will be within
the repo servers and will allow for faster deployments,
upgrades, and more consistent deployments for the life cycle
of the deployment.

commit_message:
Implement shippable venvs

The change builds venvs in a single repo container and then
ships them to to all targets. The built venvs will be within
the repo servers and will allow for faster deployments,
upgrades, and more consistent deployments for the life cycle
of the deployment.

This will create a versioned tarball that will allow for
greater visablility into the build process as well as giving
deployers/developers the ability to compair a release in
place.

Change-Id: Ieef0b89ebc009d1453c99e19e53a36eb2d70edae
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Implement L3HA support

This change enables L3HA using the neutron internals by default. This should
make the general Neutron router support more robust.

Note:
  * The ability will not effect running routers so upgrades are seemless.
  * The l3ha support is only rendered by default when using the ML2 plugin.
  * The ATT neutron l3HA tool is still needed as a backup to ensure that the
    routers are always scheduled to an agent and will remain to facilitate
    L3HA on routers created without the ha capability.

Upgrade notes:
 - neutron_ha_vrrp_advert_int (removed)
 - neutron_ha_vrrp_auth_password (moved to user_secrets.yml)
 - neutron_handle_internal_only_routers (removed)
 - neutron_l3_ha_enabled (removed)

rest: deserialize directly with file descriptor

This avoids useless memory allocation in a temporary
str between body read and json.loads.

commit_message:
UTC/Browser time as timestamp display format

Removed Z from the end of string if timestamp format is not UTC.
Having Z if browser local timestamp format is chosen is
confusing for the user because Z clearly marks given date as UTC.

Change-Id: Id2d1697192260e17d8d1a0d39ed25a835eeb3a09

commit_message:
Changing the confidence in the oslo secret plugin

This commit changes the confidence rating for the various detection
modes of the oslo secret plugin.  It had lowered the severity for
the less obvious cases, but this was probably done before we had
confidence.  Now with confidence that is the appropriate field to
lower.

Change-Id: Id0f21fcd48d6b052a4a5f3808933d937f0202913

commit_message:
Use `gulp unit` instead of calling karma directly.

When running Karma directly, Angular views are never compiled,
causing tests to fail. This replaces the direct call to karma with
`gulp unit` so views are compiled before karma is run.

Change-Id: I30b0ac39111b95755e6c8b4ec92646a3d3571b80

[{'created': '2015-10-23 04:11:22.000000000', 'message': "Add debug logging to iterate timeout

Output a debug message in each iterate timeout loop that we're waiting.

commit_message:
Add debug logging to iterate timeout

Output a debug message in each iterate timeout loop that we're waiting.
It's entirely possible that this will become noise, but it's also
silencable by setting a null handler for shade._utils.

Change-Id: I908040e4bfaaa0abd3eeb254af3bfea2fc40626c

commit_message:
Change the fallback on server wait to 2 seconds

The original iterate_timeout default was 2 seconds - but the
introduction of per-service cache timing support falls back to 0 - which
is pretty extreme. Set the fallback to 2.

Change-Id: I0163e3a3397e5a7bca22bd4bbaaca63509a072b6

commit_message:
Fix run pass or fail evaluation

Previously, if a run doesn't have any test passing or failing, it was
accounted as a run that passed.

This was portraying an optimistic view of the health of the projects.

This commit shows that code for evaluating what is a passing run is
scattered across python and different javascript functions. This is
something that should be addressed on a subsequent commit.

Change-Id: Icda130607da6ef9835a918ffb2943f0585d6c049
Co-Authored-By: Moises Trovo <mtrovo@thoughtworks.com>

commit_message:
Mark for removal deadcode in neutron.common.utils

Methods:
 * read_cached_file(filename, cache_info, reload_func=None)
 * find_config_file(options, config_file)
 * get_keystone_url(conf)
are not used withing neutron projects.

Change-Id: Iba3325103f5c24c1822781382f4c8864eb2921c5
Closes-bug: #1508430

commit_message:
Pass unicode to io.open

We must pass unicode objects (unicode in py2, str in py3) to io.open,
otherwise it would fail with:

    TypeError: can't write str to text stream

Change-Id: I9d2ba46ae6b967feb64fe180f9a6ce85918b0791
Closes-Bug: #1509325

commit_message:
Support the server side remote-console API changes

In microversion 2.6 the remote-console API was changed.
See http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/api_microversion_history.html
for details of those changes.

This adds support for the new remote-console API.

Change-Id: I67098d6ce8c71f3ac0073628fd3b0aa23cd81918
Closes-Bug: #1500688

commit_message:
Restore auth_uri for neutron::server

neutron::server requires auth_uri value to be set
or else the default value in the RPM will be used,
which is http://localhost:5000/.

Added spec for openstack::network class and tested
this parameter enforcement

Change-Id: Ia8fd95b60ab310a7e57251e099eb461c26e85c7d

Remove unused code in domain config checking

There was some unused code in the file-based code path for
domain specific configs. This patch removes it.

Closes-Bug: #1466772

commit_message:
Merge tag '11.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 11.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 11.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Iff3a4a4547842167443e507a739d839e750e1ef9

commit_message:
Move deps & external hooks into a standalone class

Previously the anchors and dependencies that allow external hooks were
all in the main ::heat class.  However, if you wanted to include just
::heat::db::mysql, then it would fail, since it assumed the main heat
class was included.  This moves all of those resources and relationships
into a new class, ::heat::deps.  All of the classes will now include
this class so that the anchors and deps are always evaluated even if
only a portion of the classes are used, and even if ::heat isn't pulled
in.

Change-Id: I4297df160a7afae2b66c1ac76e37de313fa4fb09
Closes-Bug: #1507934

commit_message:
Set dpkg to noninteractive

Do what devstack does when installing packages: set the dpkg
frontend to 'noninteractive' so it doesn't try to use stdin/out.

Change-Id: I0401782daad4f7042c38b7e2d04be924a71004c2

commit_message:
Make DATABASES_TO_SAVE available to sub process

grenade/save-state need DATABASES_TO_SAVE to save the base release databases.
The DATABASES_TO_SAVE is updated by load_settings.

Change-Id: I023248e6416fa0e8163883226bc74a7db6f7919e
Closes-bug: #1487287

(1 comment)

I'm tempted to give this a -1 because it doesn't belong in devref until there is an implementation. The content looks good, but maybe it should be a spec unless the implementation is right around the corner."}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2015-07-09 17:50:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi all - Just discussed this a bit on IRC and there are a couple of things worth reporting here: on process, and on possible overlap with "segmented routed networks" as per https://review.openstack.org/#/c/196812/.

First, on the overlap point: here is the relevant discussion from #openstack-neutron today:

<kevinbenton> neiljerram: was there not enough overlap between carl_baldwin's
              routed networks proposal and what you need?               [17:32]
<neiljerram> kevinbenton: Very interesting question!
<neiljerram> kevinbenton, carl_baldwin: For example, one point is that the
             DHCP agent needs to know that there is no bridging of the TAP
             interfaces on the compute host.
<neiljerram> With Carl's proposal, there is still bridging, so the DHCP agent
             doesn't need to change; it just needs to be run in more places,
             one per L2 segment.                                        [17:34]
<carl_baldwin> The big difference that I see is that mine segments in to L2
               domains which can easily be represented by Neutron networks
               (the backing networks).  neiljerram ’s confines L2 all the way
               to the port to accomplish only what is needed to bootstrap an
               instance on to an L3 network.
<neiljerram> Whereas with a fully routed network implementation, the DHCP
             agent needs to invoke Dnsmasq differently, to handle that.
<kevinbenton> carl_baldwin: makes sense
<neiljerram> carl_baldwin: agreed
<kevinbenton> neiljerram: what do you mean the tap interfaces have no
              bridging?
<carl_baldwin> I haven’t been able to reconcile the two in to one proposal in
               my mind.
<neiljerram> kevinbenton: On the compute host, there is the TAP interface
             to/from a VM, and it's not plugged into any kind of bridge.
<neiljerram> So a packet from a VM drops into the Linux network stack, and
             needs to be routed on to its destination
<kevinbenton> neiljerram: oh, so dnsmasq is attaching directly to every VM's
              tap interface then?                                       [17:37]
<neiljerram> kevinbenton: Yes:  --listen=tap* --bridge-interface=ns-XXX,tap*
<kevinbenton> neiljerram: ok

In summary, there's enough of a question in this area, that it makes sense for work on these two proposals to proceed independently for now.  If it turns out that there is genuine commonality in the API or implementation for these proposals, fine, and I will certainly keep that possibility in mind.

On the process point, next step is for the RFE bug for this proposal to be discussed at the next neutron-drivers IRC meeting, on Tuesday at 8AM PST / 15.00 UTC.  I hope to get a go ahead at that meeting for proceeding further with this work, and advice about exactly what form that should take.'}, {'account_id': 10327, 'date': '2015-07-13 03:31:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck db2-test'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-13 04:44:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Today's neutron-drivers meeting discussed how to continue discussion of this proposal.  Please see:

- http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-meeting/%23openstack-meeting.2015-07-14.log.html#t2015-07-14T15:18:15

- http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-meeting/%23openstack-meeting.2015-07-14.log.html#t2015-07-14T15:29:49

In summary, it wasn't clear whether the correct process is to proceed as a devref (in neutron) or as a spec (in neutron-specs), but we agreed to continue as a devref for now.  Carl is separately going to ask for clarification on the process."}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2015-07-16 13:42:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sean, Ryan - Your question is still outstanding about whether there is overlap between this and Carl Baldwin's spec at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/196812/.  I'll do my best to answer that fully here.

First, at the use case level: on the face of it we are trying to accommodate different things.

- Carl is addressing a request from some large operators who say that:

  - their physical data center network is partitioned into several L2 segments, with routing between them

  - their workloads are such that they can be scheduled to a host on any of those segments

  - therefore, the Neutron UI should present a network - for VMs to potentially attach to - that is logically the union of a set of similar L2 segments

  - but also the VM IP addressing still needs to be sane, in that the IP address chosen for a VM should match the prefix of the L2 segment that the chosen compute host is actually on.

- Whereas I am trying to accommodate the idea of providing connectivity between VMs by routing the data everywhere, instead of using bridges and tunnels to simulate a L2 broadcast domain between VMs attached to the same network.  (With projectcalico.org being one actual implementation of this idea, but not the only possible implementation.)

However, there are at least 4 points of similarity hiding behind those apparently different things.

- In both cases, only IP-level connectivity is guaranteed, between any pair of VMs attached to the same network.

- They are both trying to increase the size that a single data center can straightforwardly scale to.

- I believe they are both focussed more initially on shared networks, rather than on per-tenant networks.

- Routed networks will likely need a similar kind of 'sane' IP addressing as the segmented networks need, so that routers in the data center fabric can aggregate lots of VM routes together into prefixes.

On the other hand, there is at least 1 point where they unambiguously differ.  If we look at the set of VMs on a given compute host that are attached to the same network:

- in the segmented case, those VMs' TAP interfaces are bridged together, and either to the provider network, or to tunnels to the other relevant compute hosts

- in the routed case, those VMs' TAP interfaces are not bridged; instead data to/from them is routed, even if between VMs on the same host.

I think a central point is how the 'sane' IP addressing is achieved.  Carl does this by introducing the front and backing networks idea, with subnets being defined on the backing networks.  However Mark McClain raised an issue with that yesterday on IRC, that the port that an ML2 driver sees will likely have an unexpected network ID - i.e. that of the backing network and not of the front network.  That still needs further discussion, so no idea yet if it is a serious problem.

For 'routed' networks I haven't yet specified anything about 'sane' IP addressing, but my feeling is that this should be a perfect case for using pluggable IPAM.  In other words:

- Nova chooses the host for a VM, and asks Neutron to create the port

- Neutron asks a pluggable IPAM module to assign an IP address, telling it the chosen host

- the IPAM module uses (out-of-band) knowledge about where that host is in the physical network, to assign an appropriate IP address.

I understand that the IPAM interfaces as they stand don't support passing the chosen host, but I'd be happy to work on proposing and implementing that as an enhancement.

If that flies, I believe it would work for the 'segmented' case too, and would avoid Mark McClain's issue because then backing networks would not be needed; instead the subnet union could be specified on the front network.

So, what other parts of the solutions are there, where unification might be considered?  There are two proposed provider:network_type values, 'routed_segments' and 'routed', and I believe that these need to remain different because they describe fundamentally different ways of implemented the connectivity on each relevant compute host, and between compute hosts.  I believe it's correct for these to be different, in just the same way as existing types like 'gre' and 'vlan' are different.

Also different DHCP agent behavior is needed for 'routed_segments' and 'routed', as shown by the change at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/197578/.  Currently this is triggered by DHCP agent config (interface_driver = RoutedInterfaceDriver), but possibly that should evolve to depend dynamically on network_type - and then again it will be crucial for 'routed' to be a distinct value.

In summary, then, I believe that a partial unification of this and Carl's spec may be achievable by enhancing and using pluggable IPAM to achieve the common requirement for partitioned IP addressing.  But it's correct IMO that the two specs use different values for provider:network_type.

Please let me know what you think!"}, {'account_id': 13734, 'date': '2015-07-16 13:55:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Just one clarification to my previous comment....

For my own interest in Neutron supporting 'routed' networking, the pluggable IPAM idea is a phase 2 thing.  In other words it's absolutely useful to merge just the 'routed' network_type first, together with this devref and associated DHCP agent changes; and to work on the pluggable IPAM idea as a further value add later.

So, please don't think that my suggested pluggable IPAM enhancement is a pre-requisite for merging the 'routed' network_type work described in this devref."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-07-17 16:11:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

IMO we don't want to default gateways. By my own network isolation testing Fedora actually fails in this configuration. Centos seems to allow it with one defroute having a higher metric... I've actually pushed several approaches upstream to deal with this already my favorite of which is now just to use a static ctlplane network.

So actually the issue here is I'm missing a Depends-on: for this patch:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/206022/

Once upstream CI is actually working I'll add this."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-08-27 14:12:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

if we don't want 2 default gateways, then that's something the validation could (and should) test for, instead of the code failing in a non-obvious way. it's a scenario that could still occur, even with a static ctlplane, depending on networking configuration of interfaces outside of the control of tht/os-net-config.

so if the ping test is going to assume 1 default gateway (which isn't a valid assumption imo), then there should be a previous test that fails when there's more than 1 gateway."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-09-12 12:05:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-09-17 12:29:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Add validation to ping the default gateway(s)

This patch adds a new function that runs on all nodes so that
all default gateways are ping tested early on during the
installation process (before any puppet is executed)

Note: this change depends on the static control plane network IPs
because some distros allow/create multiple default routes without
this patch (see depends-on below).

Depends-On: Ib267e6dcf2d5ff77f7a82ee20a123965c2d07565

Change-Id: Ida125e79f3e549cae66be9dbd562197afa6400a5

[{'created': '2015-10-23 00:34:11.000000000', 'message': "Distinguish between formatted and simple commands

Originally shell=True did not check what kind of command is being run.
This patch extends the logic to treat static strings differently than
computed ones (but still, not ignore them).

New checks are split into 3 categories: computed string, static string
with special shell chars, and simple static string. Those have
respectively HIGH, MEDIUM and LOW severity.

New results:

> Issue: subprocess call with shell=True seems safe, but may be changed
> in the future, consider rewriting without shell
   Severity: Low   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:24
24subprocess.check_output('/bin/ls -l', shell=True)

>> Issue: call with shell=True contains special shell characters,
>> consider moving extra logic into Python code
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:26
26subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls *', shell=True)

>> Issue: subprocess call with shell=True identified, security issue.
   Severity: High   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:27
27subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls %s' % ('something',), shell=True)
28subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls {}'.format('something'), shell=True)

Change-Id: Ib5dde50cd12d2648cd3d67d449b9578e9f2943db
Closes-bug: 1509061

commit_message:
Distinguish between formatted and simple commands

Originally shell=True did not check what kind of command is being run.
This patch extends the logic to treat static strings differently than
computed ones (but still, not ignore them).

New checks are split into 3 categories: computed string, static string
with special shell chars, and simple static string. Those have
respectively HIGH, MEDIUM and LOW severity.

New results:

> Issue: subprocess call with shell=True seems safe, but may be changed
> in the future, consider rewriting without shell
   Severity: Low   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:24
24subprocess.check_output('/bin/ls -l', shell=True)

>> Issue: call with shell=True contains special shell characters,
>> consider moving extra logic into Python code
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:26
26subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls *', shell=True)

>> Issue: subprocess call with shell=True identified, security issue.
   Severity: High   Confidence: High
   Location: examples/subprocess_shell.py:27
27subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls %s' % ('something',), shell=True)
28subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls {}'.format('something'), shell=True)

co-authored-by: Tim Kelsey <tim.kelsey@hpe.com>
Change-Id: Ib5dde50cd12d2648cd3d67d449b9578e9f2943db
Closes-bug: 1509061

commit_message:
functional tests: wait for 'output' field

console output can be returned not in the first request by Amazon.
so tests must wait for no exception in get_console_output
and then for output field in result.

Change-Id: Iaf0549a185d2bf99dc83aea8f8272f2bf0ae5282

commit_message:
Caches Security Group Rule ACLs

In order to avoid querying for the mentioned WMI objects, adds
a cache for them, verifying the existence of the Security Group
Rules using the cache instead.

Adds the Weight field to the SecurityGroupRuleR2 in order for the
objects to have the same fields as the ACLs.

Partial-Bug: #1505196

Change-Id: I63d5984f3f9343e32e065f219567c4a821eb997b

commit_message:
Fix target resolution mismatch in neutron, nova, heat

Some tempest tests were failing because of NoSuchMethod,
UnsupportedVersion and other missed endpoint errors.

This fix provides new listener per each target and
more straight-forward matchmaker target resolution logic.

Change-Id: I4bfb42048630a0eab075e462ad1e22ebe9a45820
Closes-Bug: #1501682

I think this is an anti feature for reasons that mordred and sdague and I have discussed at the juno summit. Devstack gate is a specific tool to run devstack in order to test openstack. Openstack and devstack do not have arbitrary feature branches as described so this is really just a downstream feature. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, but it changes the relationship a bit between upstream and downstream in ways that should be considered before approving this chnage.

IMO downstream should use upstreams branch schema if they want to use upstream's tooling. Particularly since we cannot test downstream for them to ensure that we don't break them on changes to d-g.

Currently reserving my vote as I would like to see this discussed in a more inclusive manner (this change may be a good venue for that or even an infra spec)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-21 00:18:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Allow for an alternate fallback branch

Check the environment for a branch to fall back to, using the master
branch if one isn't specified in the environment.

Change-Id: I01237c7c59be46a1d7d7a19c79d288cacb73d66c

Xtrabackup previously used a hardcoded datadir.  In the latest
update to xtrabackup, the my.cnf config option datadir is now
parsed.  This variable was unset, causing galera to implode.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I523d1989575dbe24a891fcae3b6bf56d83e69615
Closes-Bug: #1509281
(cherry picked from commit 3842391b7836e1fa63131258c610920d617b624b)
'}]
commit_message:
Encode datadir for xtrabackup

Xtrabackup previously used a hardcoded datadir.  In the latest
update to xtrabackup, the my.cnf config option datadir is now
parsed.  This variable was unset, causing galera to implode.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I523d1989575dbe24a891fcae3b6bf56d83e69615
Closes-Bug: #1509281
(cherry picked from commit 3842391b7836e1fa63131258c610920d617b624b)

of EL6.  To match binary ABIs, it is recommended to use the same
major version of EL for CentOS.

commit_message:
Use EL7 repostitory instead of EL6 for percona

This patch uses the EL7 binary bits for percona's software instead
of EL6.  To match binary ABIs, it is recommended to use the same
major version of EL for CentOS.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I1d2b146a036806c7fd2baef97a6ed861a570d26e
Partial-Fix: #1509281
(cherry picked from commit a40989c002a3341f98eaf4c213401960ab489a52)

information from environment can be given because OpenStack

information and rack/network architectures. But these important
data are definitely existed in the environment.

3. Most of the existing softwares don't provide Restful API.
Other applications like OpenStack cannot interact with them.

I think OpenStack operators can greatly benefit from pandaman.

commit_message:
Introduce ITDB Service for OpenStack

Pandaman(ITDB service) is designed to provide asset management
for infrastructure powered by OpenStack.

The ASSET defined here includes both physical assets and virtual
assets in the cloud, including hardware, software, relations,
geography, people, racks, topologies, applications, etc.

Asset management is very important for data center management
and operation. As more and more data centers are powered by
OpenStack, these traditional asset management softwares are
not satisfied.

1. When operating an OpenStack clouds, operators should
simultaneously watch asset management software, which was
previously set up in the data center, and watch OpenStack
Horizon/Ceilometer. They cannot get a central and global view of
both physical and virtual assets.

2. When designing fine-grained scheduling algorithms, no further
information from environment can be given because OpenStack
doesn't know about them, especially for those geographical
information and rack/network architectures. But these important
data are definitely existed in the environment.

3. Most of the existing softwares don't provide Restful API.
Other applications like OpenStack cannot interact with them.

I think OpenStack operators can greatly benefit from pandaman.

Change-Id: I3a6eb1cdbbedef31fd126b2920229349908b3439

commit_message:
Fix show_image_direct_url value for glance-api

show_image_direct_url should be set to false
when swift is used in glance backend by default.
It fixes potential vulnerability in glance.
In another cases default for this parameters is true.

Change-Id: I3dc8ffe65d98e8ce03fddeb966503901c543272e
Closes-bug: #1498615

commit_message:
Check for unintrospected nodes before deploy

Overcloud deploy command fails after timeout when deploing on nodes which
were not discovered.

This patch adds validation check, which can stop overcloud deploy immediately.

Change-Id: Idc2335322d32507b0be9cbbba292a6bf97b98ce1
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1265069

commit_message:
Gate neutron-lbaas on -minimal job

The job is executed as part of neutron gate, so we should not leave a
hole when a neutron-lbaas can break the job by e.g. breaking the gate
hook for this specific job.

Change-Id: I4524f01431f42744b6d189394a887c7f0a9ec496
Related-Bug: #1505932

commit_message:
Add a non-voting Ironic job to Neutron

Ironic gate depends on Neutron, but nothing is run there to prevent
it from breaking like in bug #1507558. This change adds one of main
Ironic dsvm jobs as a non-voting check job to Neutron.

Change-Id: I5547b44b7b5a4bd334003425bfe8b8d1b063bac4

commit_message:
Be explicit about projects list for reqs and pbr

The requirements and pbr jobs currently rely on devstack-gate to have an
opinion on which projects are interesting. Unfortunately this means all
d-g jobs ever setup all the projects which takes a lot of time. We can
save time by removing opinion from d-g and pushing it into the jobs
themselves. This change ensures that we retain the same level of test
coverage with requirements and pbr by pushing the old projects list into
their integration jobs.

Depends-On: I875641a5d00bc8afad97cbca6760ce66ac4a5c15
Change-Id: Ife6161a4b3cfce5041fe8e6f2c128dee14208b8c

commit_message:
Add Kingbird to the project list

Kingbird is a centralized OpenStack service that
provides resource operation and management across
multiple OpenStack instances in a multi-region
OpenStack deployment. This service is part of the
OPNFV Multisite project that intends to address
the use cases related to distributed cloud environments.

Change-Id: I2716d8280db8316a34d18ebf3be501a93eef4356

commit_message:
(Re)add midonet tempest jobs

gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v1:
    tempest job using v1 plugin
    non-voting

gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-v2:
    tempest job using v2 plugin
    non-voting

gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet-ml2:
    tempest job using ml2 plugin
    experimental

Note: All jobs are api-based (vs task-based) at this point

Change-Id: Ibb865359540854423a262b0b8f56d27cfcb95066

commit_message:
Enable voting for fuel-library gates

This change adds the fuel-library gates into place with voting.
Additionally this change includes non-voting puppet 4 syntax and unit
check jobs.

Change-Id: Ief764906b14e183deef7d9496afd93c06a05bbc9
Depends-On: I93800486b5d8e0f4cd06e6d583d8fecfa28d9a52

commit_message:
Add gates for deploying Kolla

This adds three additional gates. These new gates will deploy and test
OpenStack. In contrast to the existing gates, these new gates will
only build a subset of the images Kolla provides. It will only build
those needed to deploy OpenStack.

Change-Id: I2c94eac72c61385fe6472a95ea3c9cafa33bc22d
Depends-On: I7a24a704023cc8f19d42844636e9cb512060f693

Thanks Victor for your comment. No problem for me to zip the package and use "murano package-import"; in fact, it was my first idea, but then I saw that the Core library used murano-manage.

I didn't know this sort of addition to Devstack required an approved blueprint; I sent the review request because I found the commit useful to me.

I would be glad to come at next Murano weekly meeting. Is there a predifined agenda? How can I add this to the agenda?'}, {'account_id': 13962, 'date': '2015-10-10 14:40:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Oliver, you can find any information about murano meetings here:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/MuranoAgenda#Next_meetings

Just log in with your openID and tap to edit button near Agenda title =)

P.S. io.murano - is core library of murano, that needed for all applications.
Using murano-manage for importing package leads to null tenant_id in app object model. 
This is ok for io.murano, because it should be shared between tenants and provided by murano at all.
But didn't ok for applications. Application should have tenant_id as is.

BTW, about your patch. It looks, that smth went wrong. If this one will be approved, I suggest you to do this action optional.
Smth like :

if [[ -n "$MURANO_APPLICATIONS_IMPORT" ]]; then
    your_action_here
fi

And set this variable to False by default.'}, {'account_id': 12597, 'date': '2015-10-12 04:14:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I like this idea. But please use "murano pakcage-import" instead of "murano-manage" as Victor mentioned. And I think it would be better to use "murano pacakge-import FQN" to avoid pull murano-apps repo.'}, {'account_id': 10507, 'date': '2015-10-12 09:10:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 10507, 'date': '2015-10-12 09:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

This is still a work-in-progress with the use "murano package-import".

This uses the murano service account to import the packages. This account has no admin role, so it is not possible to use "--is-public". Therefore, the imported packages are private, which is useless.

@Lin Yang, I did not use "murano pacakge-import FQN" because it enables me to import packages which are not in the repository (e.g. Guacamole), and to specify the git branch to use (e.g. development of the application on a new branch).

NB: There are CI errors with this commit, but they're not related to the change. They are regressions due to commit e407186cc3ea00 in Horizon.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-12 09:51:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

@Ekaterina, this is a DevStack patch. DevStack is not a production deployment, it is a tool for developers who want to work with the development versions of things. It should not be limited to production-grade releases of murano apps, while apps.o.o is intended to host only the final things.
 
So, for DevStack I'd really prefer to have the ability to install apps from git - and probably not only from openstack/murano-apps repo but from any other arbitrary repo (in the same way as devstack plugins work). That's a longer story, of course, but the work Olivier is doing here is a step in the right direction, IMO."}, {'account_id': 8127, 'date': '2015-10-19 09:22:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10507, 'date': '2015-10-19 09:29:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for your comments.

@Ekaterina, ok to discuss it on #murano!

@Alexander, I did not add it to the README files because it is something common to DevStack, but with this patch, you can of course chose your git repo and your git branch with 	MURANO_APPS_REPO and MURANO_APPS_BRANCH.

I recognize that the fact that this patch proposes no dependency resolution is a big limitation: to import DockerJenkins, I had to set:

MURANO_APPS="io.murano.apps.docker.Interfaces,io.murano.apps.docker.DockerStandaloneHost,io.murano.apps.docker.kubernetes.KubernetesCluster,io.murano.apps.docker.kubernetes.KubernetesPod,io.murano.apps.docker.DockerJenkins"

Perhaps we can use package-import + FQDN and add the support of a git repository instead of an app catalog. But I hoped that this patch, which suits my immediate needs, would still be helpful!'}, {'account_id': 7549, 'date': '2015-10-19 09:46:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Import packages from murano-apps in Devstack

This commit adds a Devstack MURANO_APPS variable which can be used to
install directly from the Git murano-apps repository (repository and
branch customizable) some Murano packages.

E.g MURANO_APPS="io.murano.apps.apache.Tomcat,io.murano.apps.Guacamole"

The murano-apps repository is cloned only if at least one application
is defined in MURANO_APPS.

Implements: blueprint import-apps-devstack
Change-Id: I57f959ddafd62cc726d4f5f80fec27bc86bf05d1

commit_message:
Properly deal with magnum-ui for Zanata

magnum-ui is a special snowflake in that its project name is magnum-ui,
but the directory base for source and translations is magnum_ui. Since
it's a Django project, it also isn't treated like a general Python
project anyway, so treat it like django_openstack_auth, by performing
a little refactoring.

Since the repo now contains files, and is marked for translations in
projects.yaml anyway, enable it for translations jobs.

Change-Id: I7eb73181cccae6d4bfb81848d39099d3502a044c

[{'created': '2015-10-23 10:20:49.000000000', 'message': 'Encode datadir for xtrabackup

Xtrabackup previously used a hardcoded datadir.  In the latest
update to xtrabackup, the my.cnf config option datadir is now
parsed.  This variable was unset, causing galera to implode.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I523d1989575dbe24a891fcae3b6bf56d83e69615
Closes-Bug: #1509281
'}]
commit_message:
Encode datadir for xtrabackup

Xtrabackup previously used a hardcoded datadir.  In the latest
update to xtrabackup, the my.cnf config option datadir is now
parsed.  This variable was unset, causing galera to implode.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I523d1989575dbe24a891fcae3b6bf56d83e69615
Closes-Bug: #1509281

commit_message:
Use EL7 repostitory instead of EL6 for percona

This patch uses the EL7 binary bits for percona's software instead
of EL6.  To match binary ABIs, it is recommended to use the same
major version of EL for CentOS.

backport: liberty

Change-Id: I1d2b146a036806c7fd2baef97a6ed861a570d26e
Partial-Fix: #1509281

commit_message:
Add Fuel Master IP if configuring DNS settings post-deploy

Post-deploy settings should include Fuel Master IP as the
first nameserver entry. Adding it early on causes delays
in deployment (because it does not respond), but it gets
added later during puppet run when Cobbler is up and
running dnsmasq.

Change-Id: I733f9b616cacccab4a914cc5610b60be888abda4
Depends-On: I001bb683b66fe3c4549e0584c5e51353bd7a37ab
Depends-On: If823c100f97452bbe1eef3be1f8f0943a32527cd
Related-Bug: #1503616

commit_message:
Add post-deployment rules for PXE network configuration

Fuelmenu should allow post-deployment configuration of
PXE network, but place the following restrictions:
* new_range must contain old_range in dhcp pool
* PXE interface must remain the same

For all intents and purposes, the changes are limited to
extending the range from the previously configured one.
A common use case of this would be if a user defined a /24
network for PXE, and then decided to change it to a /23
network. This would meet the user's needs and not impact
existing deployed nodes.

Change-Id: I001bb683b66fe3c4549e0584c5e51353bd7a37ab
Closes-Bug: #1503828

commit_message:
FIP was not assigned to revived Instance

When Instance with FIP was destroyed and deployed again
it lost its floating IP because after destroy it was still marked
 as occupied

Change-Id: I257883c9334d52fba6b62edccdd6e7a9b957222b
Closes-Bug: #1509066

commit_message:
Move add policy logic to cluster

This is part of an effort to move cluster action logics to clusters.
The reason is that some of these logics make need to be invoked from
other contexts (with cluster locked, certainly). The byproduct is that
the cluster action logic is greatly simplified.

Change-Id: Ie4b802a3c4a13e48d04409a9ca694745bc11a2e5

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Set Keystone endpoints to be v3 by default

This patch sets the admin, internal and public endpoints for
Keystone all to be v3 instead of the current mix of v2 for the
internal/public endpoints and v3 for the admin endpoint.

Existing deployments will have v3 endpoints added if they don't
already exist. The removal of v2 endpoints is left to the deployer
to do.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Implements: blueprint liberty-release
Change-Id: I21b600b1bfb82edd9fba900ce6a9655f9addf9ed
Closes-Bug: #1477682

Is there any way to do rearrangement like this without breaking a bunch of existing direct links to specs?

I believe every BP is connected by direct link to it's spec, so that's a lot of broken links.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:23:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Jay, which direct links were broken? Oh, you mean the ones I modified in in specs/liberty/*. Those are fine, since any URL that someone has bookmarked would be to ..specs/liberty/*. Unless someone had bookmarked something in specs/liberty-implemented/*. Sigh. Yeah, I forgot that those specs/liberty-implemented/* ones need to exist still.

I can put them back by 'hardcoding' the specs that go in 4.0 & 4.2. I wanted to see if symbolic links would work which is why I was playing with this. My ideal world (or close to ideal) would be for ALL specs to be in one directory, eg all_specs/*, and we'd have separate directories eg unimplemented, kilo, 4.0, 4.2, 4.3, etc with symbolic links to the actual specs in specs/. As it is, we already break LP because once a spec is approved we put the ../approved/<spec> URL in the LP, but after implementation, we've been moving the specs to <cycle>-implemented/, but not updating the LPs with the changed URL.

Alternatively, I can put the liberty-implemented specs in placeholders -- I'll do that for now anyway."}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-07 02:23:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-07 03:20:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-07 03:25:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I think I may be missing some context here.

So when one propose a spec it should be a "approved/", once it's implemented and the software is released someone (probably the release liaison) will create a link to it to the specific version folder?'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:17:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Seems it was already agreed to organize it this way, so removing my vote'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:19:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I explained to Lucas on IRC but I should put it here for others:

The current process is for specs to be put in approved/ subdirectory, and after it is implemented, someone (has been PTL or release manager in the past, ie jroll or devananda) submits a patch to move them to <cycle>-implemented.

I don't think it makes sense to move the files because it breaks external references, so this patch does two things for me: 1. groups the specs in the appropriate ironic version; 2. groups them w/o moving the actual spec file.

I think we can use a similar model for future specs. (What I'd like to see is all the specs in some eg 'all_specs/' subdirectory (and only delete them if they aren't valid/approved anymore), with other subdirs/symbolic-links to the actual files. But this is outside the scope of this patch. I need to convince folks first :)"}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-08 14:21:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Lucas. To be clear, the process to move specs from approved/ -> <cycle>-implemented was decided and has been followed.

Adding the new version sections and grouping the specs that way was an idea from Jay -- that's what this patch is about. So approving it means you are OK with categorizing the specs that way (and how that categorization is done) :)"}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:25:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 12356, 'date': '2015-10-08 17:25:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-20 15:02:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Organize Liberty specs into implemented versions

Now that we have semver-versioned releases of ironic, it would be
useful to show which specifications were implemented in each
release.

New subdirectories 4.0 & 4.2 are created for each ironic release
during the Liberty development cycle (where any blueprints were
implemented) and symbolic links are added to the actual
specification files in liberty-implemented/.

The specifications at liberty-implemented/ are still generated and
available at that older URL location, but we don't put any explicit
links to those older URLs in the index.

Change-Id: I3e74d6055c4d56a56e54d0f34b53e0a695c3bb50

commit_message:
Fix k8s CLI to work with Bay name

K8s CLI especially pod/rc/service show and delete works with UUID. This
patch aims to fix k8s CLI to work with bay name as well. If needed this
patch will be ported back to stable/liberty as well.

Change-Id: I2fc9352af63cb261864be9332609603fb943a165
Closes-Bug: #1509091

commit_message:
Update iSCSI drivers cleaning spec

This commit updates the iSCSI drivers cleaning spec
to avoid the proposed CONF variable to enable/disable
cleaning for these drivers. Ironic will detect if
bash ramdisk is used and act accordingly.

Change-Id: Ia6013fb164fc499c8c873417115dce9c9b1adf89

commit_message:
Detach and terminate conn if Cinder attach fails

Driver's detach volume is not called while handling
failure during Cinder attach. This can result in data
loss in the case of VMware driver since the instance
VM is not re-configured to remove volume's vmdk. Also,
the connection won't be terminated if attach fails.
This patch fixes the above issues with cleanup during
Cinder attach failure.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/virt/test_block_device.py
	nova/virt/block_device.py

Resolves rhbz: #1270886
Upstream-Kilo: https://review.openstack.org/238493
Upstream-Liberty: https://review.openstack.org/186742
Closes-bug: #1460044
Change-Id: I62c0800f68d8fd89fed98eea9e3f95d1adbe9d7f
(cherry picked from commit aa899506366cd84d5170cb913f33c0c0ca7a8b27)

If the ACL middleware throws an exception, it's not annotated
by CORS, preventing the browser from seeing the auth error.
This patch reverses the order and makes sure even auth
error responses are annotated.

Change-Id: Ie2c05fe6a7f1eb341707311d6452aaf01b4790b3
"}]
commit_message:
Switched order of CORS middleware

If the ACL middleware throws an exception, it's not annotated
by CORS, preventing the browser from seeing the auth error.
This patch reverses the order and makes sure even auth
error responses are annotated.

Change-Id: Ie2c05fe6a7f1eb341707311d6452aaf01b4790b3

commit_message:
Pinned percona-xtrabackup to ensure stability

This change makes it so that the xtrabackup plugin is pinned
to a specific version via downloading the deb.

This reinstates the galera affinity values for testing so that
we're not skipping potentially broken code paths.

Related-Bug: #1508411
Related-Bug: #1508448
Related-Bug: #1508450
Change-Id: I288d6d9871eb9dfe0ecc547e50639078afdff79d
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Combine contributor quickstart setup steps 1 and 2

Treat account setup and ICLA as one step in the Contributor Guide
Quickstart chapter. The old second step merely linked to a
subsection of the Infra Manual section linked in the first step. If
it's unclear that the CLA subsection of the Account Setup section is
mandatory, then we should improve the formatting/flow in the Infra
Manual accordingly.

Change-Id: Ie126cbc723fe11cf9b581ea87aa4c9c8f147f3b2

commit_message:
plugin_v2: Deal with the lack of portsecurity DB rows

For get methods, consider the lack of the binding row as
the API default value of network portsecurity.
(It's similar to ML2.  The reason it was necessary
for ML2 is a bit different from midonet, though.)

For update methods, create the binding row for the resource
if it isn't found.

Similar ML2 change: I73abc98d83372f6259f17680806e6541458e2077
Closes-Bug: #1507651
Change-Id: I97b128f2801b7bc5bf1ff028b7927bda068643d8

commit_message:
Make retrieve_bay support retrieve_bay from bay.

The method get_removal_nodes of ScaleManager creates a k8s_api from a bay
object, but __init__ of K8sAPI require a bay object, so we can make
retrieve_bay() support retrieve_bay from bay.

Closes-Bug: #1509206
Change-Id: I5705580ef13fd767814ad774f702ca628a382d76

commit_message:
Adds documentation on creating Oslo RequestContext in Castellan

This patch adds documentation showing how oslo.context
Request Context can be generated using keystone client. This
documentation will be useful to new Castellan users who are
no familiar with using context.

Change-Id: I60999890cd033808713595087074085bfa915181

commit_message:
Hyper-V: Adds vNUMA implementation

vNUMA can improve the performance of workloads running on virtual machines
that are configured with large amounts of memory. This feature is useful
for high-performance NUMA-aware applications, such as database or web
servers.

Returns Hyper-V host NUMA node information during get_available_resource
Adds validation for instances requiring NUMA topology (no asymmetric
topology and no CPU pinning supported).
Creates NUMA aware instances, if necessary.

Implements: blueprint hyper-v-vnuma-enable

Change-Id: Ia235b25cf9d85bac2f4a23524f8b8602f186bdaf

commit_message:
Expand test in-progress workaround

When working around bug #1450314, we changed integration tests to ignore
the lock when doing an update. Unfortunately, this issue happens for
actions other than update like delete and suspend, so let's apply the
same fix for those actions too.

Change-Id: I04c5f35a1851163bc849f5c8be0f6e865ee0088e
Closes-Bug: #1508990
Related-Bug: #1450314

commit_message:
Make haproxy tests to be rspec-puppet 2 compatible

This change pulls in the upstream commit
eef121eddf659e66e13157033496def216d69af4 to make the haproxy module
rspec-puppet 2 compatible so that they can pass under our
openstack-infra tests.

Additionally we are updating the rspec-core to ~> 3.3 to be consistent
with the other modules in fuel-library.

Change-Id: I93800486b5d8e0f4cd06e6d583d8fecfa28d9a52
Closes-Bug: #1508983

commit_message:
Fix tests for l23network

This change includes an update to rspec-puppet ~> 2.2 and adjusting the
two tests that fail under 2.2 but not 2.1. I believe these failures are
related to https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/issues/266

The get_network_role_properly was previously passing because the return
value was not be properly check. In the code we are returning eth0 as
the interface for the admin network role and not nil.

The get_transformation_property was previously passing because the
return value was not correctly checked. Based on the code, the value for
eth2 should have been 1024 while the value for eth3 would have been nil.
This change updates the eth2 check with 1024 and adds a test case for
eth3.

Change-Id: I7b87d02d4c702dde68ecd7f4abcd304e686fa795
Closes-Bug: #1509056

commit_message:
Update networking-cisco plugin requirements

apicapi 1.0.4 does not support oslo.config new description.
  (i.e changes from oslo.config to oslo_config)
but updated apicapi is already supported.
switch from pip to github.

Change-Id: I6f9802b4a8b8737b2fa3697150a973c046b9ea30
Related-Bug: #1503967

commit_message:
Delete openstack folder to advoid import issue

This project dependends on openstacksdk, but also a folder use the same name
as "openstack", which will cause import issue.

This patch remove folder "openstack" and remove the only one python module
"cliutils.py" to senlinclient/common.

Change-Id: If432386176ab222577d337aa05f1de1fce4fb7d8
Closes-Bug:#1508100

commit_message:
Removed unused return value from AsyncProcess

This private function was returning True/False arbitrarily
from _kill_process.  I removed the return statements.

After checking Hound, I could see no instances where the return
value meant anything to a calling function.

Change-Id: I4419c7ac724789f0b0a9f56c5b121c7dc99d5019
Closes-Bug: #1508530

messages:
[{'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-20 20:48:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:08:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:14:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-20 21:36:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

- gate-ironic-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/73/237773/2/check/gate-ironic-python34/32d7a82/ : SUCCESS in 9m 46s'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-20 23:40:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Hi John, I just looked quickly. Dem are a lot of changed files. What if the test classes diverge, and we end up wanting them slightly different for units vs functional? I almost wonder if we should have a tests.unit.base.py that inherits from tests.base.py, and similarly for tests.functional.base.py. (Just a thought.)'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-20 23:58:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Ruby,

For functional testing I will be creating a functional testing class which will depend on ironic.tests.base

At the moment in my WIP for that it is in ironic.tests.functional.__init__  But still in WIP phase there.

If do decide to diverge the base & unit classes in the future I would think that would be a separate patch set. What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-20 23:59:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-10-21 00:00:16.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to ironic-functional'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2015-10-21 00:06:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

John, my thinking was that if we thought we might want to subclass base for unit tests, then why not do it now so that all/most of those files in tests/unit/* don't have to be modified now and modified again later. And if we don't think we will need to subclass base for unit tests, would it hurt to subclass it anyway so we don't have to modify all those tests.

I guess I'd prefer to subclass it, especially since you mentioned subclassing it for functional tests. That puts them on equal footing."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-21 00:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Move ironic.tests.unit.base to ironic.tests.base

We will use the base.py file for both unit and functional testing, so
move it under ironic/tests/base.py

Change-Id: Ifc36d61be60c820dd8e5ee0f9b9dadb52d8b480a
Partial-Bug: #1491670

commit_message:
Move hash_ring refresh logic out of sync_local_state

As sync_local_state periodic task can be disabled, which will lose
out on hash ring refresh, so the refresh logic should be independent
of it. this patch adds a updated_at to HashRingManager to track of
when the ring was last refreshed, and when checks the ring is set,
also check the age and rebuild if older than the new config option
hash_ring_reset_interval which is default to 180s.

Change-Id: Ie46dbf93b920543f99e11774a29878aaf27c3400
Closes-Bug: #1506657

commit_message:
Out-of-band hardware inspection support for Cisco B/C/M-series
servers

This spec adds support for inspecting Cisco UCSM managed B/C/M-series
servers. Fetches node's required properties, and capabilities specific to
hardware model.

Change-Id: I0b728ed7470ca5948987be4b0c75eca9f4b1698f

commit_message:
Temporary disable etcd publish-subscribe

Sometimes etcd updates are not spotted by the local controller,
until this problem is investigated its better to work in poll mode.

Change-Id: I234fdfab4fb77dba93017003f2bc8320497a85cb

commit_message:
Properly handle segmentation_id in OVS agent

The segmentation_id of a OVS VLAN can be None, but a recent change
assumed that it was always an integer. It highlighted the fact that we
try to store None in the OVS database, which got stored as a string.
This fixes the storage, and handles loading the value while keeping
compatibility.

Change-Id: I6e7df1406c90ddde254467bb87ff1507a4caaadd
Closes-Bug: #1494281
(cherry picked from commit 51f6b2e1c9c2f5f5106b9ae8316e57750f09d7c9)

[{'created': '2015-10-20 17:40:06.000000000', 'message': 'Deploy listener configuration in order

This patch accomplishes the following:
1. Makes sure the configuration and certificates are deployed to
   the amphora in the correct order
2. Only loop across the amps for a given listener once to deploy the
   updated configuration and/or certificates.

Change-Id: I2039b04e409a751847a7c4b0923de22911c72e39
Closes-Bug: #1507723
'}, {'created': '2015-10-21 00:18:53.000000000', 'message': 'Bypass listener check on cert deploy during create

This patch allows the certificate deployment code to bypass
the check for an existing listener configuration on the amphora
during the listener create process.

Change-Id: I2039b04e409a751847a7c4b0923de22911c72e39
Closes-Bug: #1507723
'}]
commit_message:
Bypass listener check on cert deploy during create

This patch allows the certificate deployment code to bypass
the check for an existing listener configuration on the amphora
during the listener create process.

Change-Id: I2039b04e409a751847a7c4b0923de22911c72e39
Closes-Bug: #1507723

commit_message:
Install device-mapper-multipath on overcloud-full

device-mapper-multipath needs to be installed for managing of multipath
devices for scenarios where fail over or load balancing of block devices
is desirable.

This change installs the package by default in the overcloud-full image
for connvenience. The multipathd daemon is not started or enabled nor
any multipath configuration exposed. Those exercises would be left to be
done via the ExtraConfig resources in tripleo-heat-templates.

Change-Id: I5b575fe7728fd58c1fd448b1f4355ee4df7bffb8

commit_message:
Use `region` or `region_id` in a consistent way

`region` is used in V2 API while `region_id` is used in V3 API,
and `region_id` is also added into V3 API for backward compatibility,
this is done in the SQL backend. In order to make it consistently
between different backends, we also need add `region_id`
into endpoints while the backend is not SQL.

Change-Id: I9c44696b8bfbc8225134b720063534a8f774d9b6
Closes-Bug: #1429566

commit_message:
Always send status update for processed floating ips

Currently l3 agent skips status update for floating ips in case
status didn't change: this might be wrong if status has changed
on server side while agent was processing. See bug for details.

L3 agent skips floating ip processing in case ip address exists
on external device. So we can still skip status update for such
floating ips.

Closes-Bug: #1505557
Change-Id: I908fe5a0555f68ab85e7d199c36a903b915e103f
(cherry picked from commit 7592b17b8793c0e296c77bd17929f3db37f1483e)

commit_message:
CreateVM supports subnet specified

Currently the network info specified as part of
server creation is limited to network-id, port-id,
and ip address. When a network has multiple subnets
then we need to also be able to specify a subnet-id.

APIImpact
DocImpact: see details in
nova/api/openstack/rest_api_version_history.rst

Implements: blueprint selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm
Change-Id: I31a8c02b3ec1ec1beec321f74086aebfa80c4a2f

as for unit test for the change - there's just no ready infrastructure for that kind of tests (especially because that part of the code involves process forking).

Indeed I made a typo in metering plugin and it worked because parent process still configures RPC consumer at each service plugin's __init__
So it was not really a functional issue, although kind of missed the point of the patch for metering plugin.
In other words I'm not really sure unit test makes sense here."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-10-03 14:30:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

On the testing front, I gave this a whirl locally. I ended up with this: http://paste.openstack.org/show/475238/. The problem is that we mock 'neutron.common.rpc.Connection.consume_in_threads' in BaseTestCase.setup_rpc_mocks (So that we don't actually start RPC listeners during unit tests), so _servers ends up [] even though the service plugins do implement the correct method. We could assert that each plugin called start_listeners_method, but, meh. There's little value in that. The only alternative is to do this via a functional test: Start the neutron-server process configured for ML2 + service plugins, but then I'm not sure what we would be asserting."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-10-03 14:31:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-10-03 14:48:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Consume service plugins queues in RPC workers.

This patch adds all RPC workers to consumers of service
plugins queues such as metering and l3-plugin.
This is important for DVR-enabled deployments with hundreds
of agents.

Change-Id: I6fea7f409c91b25d2c35b038d6100fdfa85d1905
Closes-Bug: #1498844

commit_message:
Support creating port with subnet_id in neutron api

Aims to booting instance with subnet_id, update some
functions in neutron api in order to creating port with
subnet_id.

Change-Id: I5af99a59b19d12885aa20c3d4ee477d4edc78159
implements: blueprint selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm

subject: Add subnet_id in NetworkRequest object

commit_message:
Add subnet_id in NetworkRequest object

Update NetworkRequest and NetworkRequestList version,
and add backward compatible logic in from_tuple().

Change-Id: Ifd22a940975ae05a947a8df4b261e6cd69132dd0
implements: blueprint selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm

Dump microversion for bp selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm

(1 comment)

This is a good demonstration of why the compute nodes concept in nova is flawed at best and incomplete at least.

Summing resources like this does not make the situation better and in fact increases confusion.

We've previously rejected functionality like this. Especially since we just merged the patch to remove the node concept from vmware, I think this is is clearly -2 worthy."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-08-29 03:24:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Actually I would like to see the host-describe API is deprecated."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-10-23 02:08:53.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Fix incorrect result of host-describe

host-describe only return the result(total, used_now)
of one compute node when we map one nova-compute to
multiple compute nodes, like: vCenter or Ironic driver.
Fix this issue, sum all of the compute nodes that related
with the nova-compute, also fix 'nova-manage service
describe_resource' in this patch.

Change-Id: I26e704091004a8d6a268c8ac385f6bc240e6ead0
Closes-Bug: #1483104

I'm still stuck on the IPv6 case. Yes, you have now put a section in your spec highlighting that for IPv6 there has already been a behavior determined. That's helpful, but your proposal just acknowledges the problem.

I guess I want to take this further and ask if it makes sense to create an API where people can specify a subnet - which is useful for the IPv4 usecase, but does it makes sense looking forward?

If a deployer has created a Neutron network and associated subnets with it, especially a Network that has both an IPv4 and IPv6 subnet associated, that means you're going to get a dual stacked instance. I don't know if it makes sense to have an API with a parameter that, depending on your network topology, will either give you what you want, or ignore it and return two subnet associations anyway. I'd rather not expose that to the user."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-06-27 02:18:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

It make sense to specify subnet to boot instance both in ipv4 and ipv6 use case when there are multiple subnets in a network.

I design the blueprint according to the current neutron behavior, and the issue we discussed should be in neutron scope, so I reopen the neutron bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1467791 and show my point in the comments. Hope to get some feedback from neutron.

And I don't think we should block this nova blueprint because of a neutron issue or design behavior."}, {'account_id': 13252, 'date': '2015-06-29 09:43:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-06-30 03:33:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

>And I don't think we should block this nova blueprint because of a neutron issue or design behavior.

I strongly disagree with this sentiment. Nova and Neutron need to work together to solve some of these issues. Filing a bug against Neutron and then saying "It's not my problem that Neutron works in a way that I disagree with" is not a reason to approve this blueprint.'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-07-01 03:55:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

I means that we should focus on nova behavior of this spec, nova just create port with specify subnet in the design workflow. So no matter it's a bug or design behavior of neutron, I think the nova behavior will not been changed in the spec and some explanation of the neutron behavior had been added in the spec.

I file the bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1467791 in neutron because I want to get some feedback from there in order to continue this works."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-07-01 10:37:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think we need to sit down and agree what to do with these networking APIs.

commit_message:
CreateVM supports subnet specified

Currently the network info specified as part of
server creation is limited to network-id, port-id,
and ip address. When a network has multiple subnets
then we should be able to specify a subnet-id.

APIImpact
DocImpact
Previously-approved: juno
blueprint selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm

Change-Id: Iadbf9dd4d24e73f96ba13587efc1818177f0df14

commit_message:
Add list of routes to / on api server

This commit adds a list of available routes as the response for a GET
on the root of the api server. It's a bit bizarre for end users to get
a 404 response when they do a GET on the API server. This will provide
users with a pointer to what's available.

Change-Id: I4da61ee74ec11bde96a99d1673e311155f126bc9

commit_message:
Refactor MagnumException to reduce complexity

Reduce cyclomatic complexity of MagnumException to below 10. Remove
exception handling and optimise the logging when the kwargs does not
match the message.

Change-Id: I4fd6ba96be9dff485cdd8bde9750f2d584c1ec63
Closes-Bug: #1501331

commit_message:
Refactor config setup to reduce complexity

The cyclomatic complexity of the setup method was greater than 10 and
reducing this complexity allows for easier understanding of the method.

Change-Id: I45d085d0943fd18a4207fc7a9ba64f2c0f8074ea
Partial-Bug: #1501331

Add functional test cases for swarm

Added both tls_enabled=True/False cases.

commit_message:
Refactor periodic task sync_bay_status

The cyclomatic complexity of sync_bay_status was greater than 10 and
very hard to comprehend. This patch reduces the complexity and makes the
task more open to refactoring and maintence.

Partial-Bug: #1501331
Change-Id: If415aa7710b586b0429ed1bc5077976791b424d1

commit_message:
Reduce complexity of poll_and_check method

This is method is overly complex and should be broken down. When
reducing the max complexity allowed by flake8 this method was flagged.
Reducing the complexity of this method will allow better testing and
maintenance.

Partial-Bug: #1501331
Change-Id: Id0bdb2d03614ba31de0d96ed09c33695d933b9f7

commit_message:
Fix l2pop regression

Patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236970/ introduced an issue
where get_agent_by_host can return a random host (Including L3,
DHCP or metadata agents), not only L2 agents. The caller then
tries to get tunneling_ip, which might not exist on the returned
agent, causing l2pop code to bail out with a WARNING:
'Unable to retrieve the agent ip...'.

The issue was found by manual introspection of the code, and
verified by modifying the l2pop fullstack test to register L3
agents. Both a unit test was added, as well as modifying the
fullstack connectivity test to register L3 agents if l2pop
is enabled.

The code will now check for agents with a tunneling_ip key
in their configurations dict, which is required for l2pop
to work correctly, essentially a form of duck typing.

(Cherry-picked from commit 204eb2af1752cbdd4d1bfc42aa4d61debdeb7551)

Change-Id: Ib3072966140b7f6ca954d7847ad9835aa1191998
Closes-Bug: #1508205

commit_message:
Use system random where applicable

One of the bandit checks is to attempt to use the system random
library (which is better at producing randomness) vs using the
default random class, this change uses the system random where
applicable.

See: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Security/Projects/Bandit

Change-Id: I15ae3c99267b2dd9dc9ceccd427f6c0aef6ae8da

commit_message:
Refactor backoff looping call

This codebase can now be updated to use the refactored
base class to avoid duplicating alot of the same code.

Eventually we should also just move this to oslo if
when/this review is accepted since that seems like a better
home for this code in general.

Change-Id: I387d60667f427824a64d52544638792429887ebf

commit_message:
Support pagination params for flavor list

Missing 'marker' and 'limit' params for `openstack flavor list` shell
command. It would be nice to have this when there are many flavors.

Closes-bug: #1505874

Since we're installing from wheels we will need to know the location of the metadefs as installed by Glance's wheel. Now that we're supporting virtual environments, this can be in two places

    /usr/local/etc/glance/metadefs (non-virtualenv)

    $(virtualenv_path)/etc/glance/metadefs (virtualenv)

Also you'll probably want to double check those paths on a test deployment to be absolutely certain.

Also this shouldn't be backported to kilo because liberty is the first release to have the setup.cfg bits that do the necessary work with the data_files argument."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-15 16:20:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

commit_message:
Change router unbinding logic to be consistent with data model

Model allows router to be bound to different agents
Code should not make assumptions that the correspondence is 1-to-1

Closes-Bug: #1497980
Change-Id: Ieda9fc6e2d5a85194f2d022ea092cefb55183750
(cherry picked from commit 30bcbf3df8d38f7940233ba60554d93dea4a0692)

commit_message:
Allow protocol to be set per endpoint-type

If services are running behind an SSL terminating LB you will want to
differentiate between protocol on internalURL and publicURL endpoints.
This patch allows you to set the values of protocol per endpoint type,
but doesn't change the default behaviour which is to have it set in one
var.

The protocol for each endpoint-type can also be set globally for all
services, e.g. internaluri can be http, and publicuri can be https
through the variables:
  - openstack_service_publicuri_proto
  - openstack_service_adminuri_proto
  - openstack_service_internaluri_proto

The following variables have been renamed for forward compatibility when
upgrading to Kilo:
  - registry_host -> glance_registry_host
  - auth_protocol -> keystone_service_proto
  - auth_public_port -> keystone_service_port
  - auth_port -> keystone_admin_port

Configuration of service ports has also been made more consistent.

Based on commits:
1a2907c6a137bc4bc110f971f34904a20a7a5ad4
2b6b896105c7d4cd3b615432da3c084fcc2bf29b

Change-Id: I9256ca9d6ffedd61e12ed7b80916f491e6ecac67
Closes-Bug: #1399383

commit_message:
Remove SUPPORTED_AGENT_TYPES for l2pop

In a world where agents can be out of tree,
this check seems no longer necessary.

As part of networking-vsphere project which runs ovsvapp agent
on each ESXi host inside service VM, which talk to neutron-server
having l2pop enabled in a multi-hypervisor mode like KVM, ESXi.
The tunnels are not getting established between KVM compute node
and ESXi host. The l2pop mech_driver needs to embrace ovsvapp agent
to form the tunnels.

Hence, this patch-set addresses the issue by removing the
SUPPORTED_AGENT_TYPES for l2pop.

(Cherry-picked from commit 07aa19b2236976229971b13e9ece80b862d298b2)

Closes-Bug: #1507684
Change-Id: I93ca5736e4aad41b851d2b7b082b4bb69d1632fb

commit_message:
Add support for Designate V2 api

* Switch to use ksc.Session instead of passing in auth info to client.
* Add support for multiple versions of Designate

Change-Id: I737dabd51fe76e8508564d9ac3d8662019be755a

By returning the need for binding, the (no-op) port processing
is skipped in the main sync loop. In fact, the port is already
detected as deleted and avoiding going over it again will save
us one log message, and thus many, many, many, many bytes over
time in logs.openstack.org.

If this is not an improvement, I don't what is.

Related-bug: 1455320

Change-Id: I4ef30bed6a1619f5980c3e61ee23ffb808c2c4f0

commit_message:
Minor improvement in port_bound operation

By returning the need for binding, the (no-op) port processing
is skipped in the main sync loop. In fact, the port is already
detected as deleted and avoiding going over it again will save
us one log message, and thus many, many, many, many bytes over
time in logs.openstack.org.

If this is not an improvement, I don't what is.

Related-bug: 1455320

Change-Id: I4ef30bed6a1619f5980c3e61ee23ffb808c2c4f0

commit_message:
Adding new RabbitMQ alarms (fd,proc,sockets)

This fix is adding alarms for existing metrics
- fd_used
- proc_used
- socket_used
and will set off alarms when any of these metrics reach 90% of the
current configured total limit. Those metrics are already exposed
as part of the rabbitmq_status.py check.

Change-Id: Ie916215c5c596a5be53b6a90e0a22b3f0f70653e
Closes-Bug: #1508207

[{'created': '2015-10-03 01:18:41.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Updated the repo-build process

This commit changes the repo build play such that it no longer
requires "yaprt". The intention here is to make the build process
less of a blackbox, simpler, and faster. With recent improvements
in OpenStack and PIP we're now able to do a lot more without the
use of the "yaprt" tool.

Change-Id: Icb0a4e3443491eb0242125ea59f8d5b50f89410b
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Updated the repo-build process

This commit changes the repo build play such that it no longer
requires "yaprt". The intention here is to make the build process
less of a blackbox, simpler, and faster. With recent improvements
in OpenStack and PIP we're now able to do a lot more without the
use of the "yaprt" tool. Repo building is now its own standalone
role.

This PR now reintroduces the repo-clone ability which is now made
smarter. The repo-build process creates a manifest file which is
used to provide the ability to sync exactly the contents of the
tagged release. This will make repeatable deployments faster for
downstream consumers.

The repo-store-source.yml play was removed because it hasn't been
used as the repo clone process is part of the main repo build
process.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Change-Id: Icb0a4e3443491eb0242125ea59f8d5b50f89410b
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Add an iboot reboot_delay setting

This patch adds a new reboot_delay setting to the iboot
power driver. This setting is important when using IPA
which can cause a power manager REBOOT which if there
is no sleep can occur so quickly the machine doesn't properly
power cycle.

The patch also updates the ironic.conf.sample file.

Closes-bug: #1504258

Change-Id: I70ec7151d0154bd6f6445bcc0e90de2dc5b380e5
